related_questions.question: Is beans good for health?
related_questions.snippet: Beans and legumes contain antioxidants that help prevent cell damage and fight disease and aging. The fiber and other nutrients benefit the digestive system and may even help prevent digestive cancers. Legumes can be added to any meal, for breakfast, lunch, or dinner.

related_questions.question: Is a bean a carbohydrate or protein?
related_questions.snippet: That's right; beans contain both carbohydrate and protein. Since beans have both carbohydrate and protein, where do they fit in a diabetes nutrition plan? Remember that beans are high in fiber. Your body doesn't digest fiber so not all of the carbohydrate from beans will be turned into blood sugar.

buttons.subtitle: Is Bean A Fruit Or Vegetable?
buttons.title: Are Beans Vegetables? Food Group, 10 Types - MedicineNet
buttons.snippet: Beans are extracted from a pod that belongs to the family Fabaceae, commonly called legumes. A legume is a plant that produces “fruit” within a pod and beans come from pods. Botanically, beans are fruits, but they can be considered both a fruit and a vegetable.

buttons.title: The 9 Healthiest Beans and Legumes You Can Eat - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Beans and legumes are excellent sources of dietary fiber, protein, B vitamins, and many other important vitamins and minerals. Some evidence suggests they can help reduce blood sugar, boost heart health, and maintain a healthy gut.

buttons.subtitle: Protein In Beans
buttons.title: Beans: Myths and Facts - Bastyr University
buttons.snippet: Let's get to the meat of some myths that may be holding you back from incorporating more beans into your diet: Myth: Beans don't have enough protein to replace meat in a meal. Fact: Different beans contain different amounts of protein. Most beans contain between 6 and 9 grams of protein per ½ cup serving.
snippet_highlighted_words: between 6 and 9 grams of protein per ½ cup serving

buttons.subtitle: Carbs In Beans
buttons.title: Legumes: Health Benefits and Culinary Approaches to Increase ...
buttons.snippet: Legumes are naturally low in fat, are practically free of saturated fat, and because they are plant foods, they are cholesterol free as well. One serving of legumes, which is one-half cup, provides about 115 calories, 20 g of carbohydrate, 7–9 g of fiber, 8 g of protein, and 1 g of fat.
